# 5. Enterprise opportunity architecture

## The opportunity hierarchy

Do not manage every idea at the same level. Use a four-layer structure.

```text
Enterprise value theme
  └── Capability / domain objective
        └── Opportunity family
              └── Specific use case / product increment
```

### Example

```text
Value theme: Improve manufacturing margin
  └── Capability objective: Reduce quality losses in critical process families
        └── Opportunity family: Earlier detection and faster investigation of process excursions
              ├── Anomaly detection
              ├── Root-cause evidence assistant
              ├── Vision-based defect classification
              └── CAPA / deviation documentation assistant
```

This hierarchy allows leadership to fund a coherent capability rather than an unconnected collection of experiments.

## The four portfolio lanes

| Lane | Characteristics | Typical duration | What success means |
|---|---|---:|---|
| **Quick wins** | High readiness; bounded workflow; visible local value. | 4–12 weeks to evidence. | Trust, adoption, measurable savings/capacity, reusable pattern. |
| **Strategic bets** | High value; multiple dependencies; cross-functional impact. | 1–4 quarters. | Differentiated capability or material operating impact. |
| **Foundation investments** | Shared identity, data, knowledge, evaluation, observability, or governance capability. | 1–4 quarters. | Multiple use cases become faster, safer, cheaper to deliver. |
| **Explore / learn** | Uncertain technology/value; learning is a valid objective. | 2–6 weeks. | Clear decision: advance, reframe, or stop. |

## The “innovation funnel” target state

The exact volumes vary by organization, but a healthy funnel should show progressive evidence, not simply large intake volume.

| Funnel stage | What is counted | Healthy sign |
|---|---|---|
| **Signals** | Raw ideas and pain points. | Broad input from business, engineering, plants, and enterprise functions. |
| **Qualified opportunities** | Clear sponsor, process, and outcome. | Low-quality technology-first requests are filtered early. |
| **Shaped opportunities** | Canvas, options, baseline, initial risk/data view. | Leaders can compare apples to apples. |
| **Funded proofs** | Time-boxed charters with success/stop thresholds. | The organization can say no to weak ideas. |
| **Scaled products** | Integrated, governed, supported workflow improvements. | Most investment is focused on a limited number of scalable priorities. |
| **Realized value** | Finance/business-confirmed benefits. | Benefits are tracked after launch, not merely forecast. |

