# 11. Business case and value-realization framework

## The five value types

| Value type | Formula concept | Evidence required |
|---|---|---|
| **Hard cost reduction** | Avoided spend or eliminated external/internal cost. | Budget/contract owner confirms a cost can actually be removed. |
| **Productivity / capacity** | Volume × time saved × adoption × usable capacity conversion × fully loaded cost. | Time study, usage data, business plan for redeploying capacity. |
| **Revenue / margin** | Improved conversion, speed, retention, yield, or price realization × contribution margin. | Baseline commercial/production data and finance-approved model. |
| **Working capital / cash** | Inventory, receivables, payables, or asset-use improvement × cost of capital / cash impact. | Finance-approved baseline and mechanism. |
| **Risk / quality / service** | Reduced incidents/errors/scrap/warranty events × expected cost per event. | Event history, quality/incident data, risk-owner validation. |

## The productivity warning

**Hours saved are not automatically financial savings.** They become value only when the business can convert them into one or more of:
- increased output without additional hiring;
- reduced overtime or contractor spend;
- redeployment to work that removes a bottleneck;
- avoided future hiring;
- reduced cycle time with a measurable commercial/operational effect.

## Value hypothesis template

```text
Outcome: Reduce time-to-triage for process excursions.

Baseline: 12 hours average from event creation to initial evidence package.
Target: 25% reduction without lower investigation completeness.
Population: 1,200 qualifying excursions per year.
Mechanism: Reallocate engineering capacity to preventive process improvement and reduce repeat-event exposure.
Owner: Plant/process engineering leader.
Measurement: Time stamps + quality review sampling + adoption telemetry.
Review points: Week 4, week 8, pilot close, quarter after deployment.
Stop condition: No material time improvement, low adoption, or quality/control threshold failure.
```

## Benefit-realization handshake

Before pilot approval, confirm this in writing.

| Field | Accountable party | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|
| Baseline metric | Process owner + finance/value lead | Stops post-pilot arguments about measurement. |
| Target | Executive sponsor | Makes the ambition explicit. |
| Measurement method | Product/delivery + data lead | Creates credible instrumentation. |
| Benefit owner | Business leader | Someone owns conversion of improvement into value. |
| Realization mechanism | Business + finance | Distinguishes impact from aspiration. |
| Review cadence | Sponsor | Ensures value tracking survives launch. |
| Stop condition | Sponsor + innovation lead | Creates permission to end weak work. |

## Pilot scorecard

| Dimension | What to measure |
|---|---|
| **Adoption** | Eligible-user activation, repeat use, workflow completion, override/abandon rate. |
| **Task quality** | Accuracy, completeness, grounded evidence, reviewer acceptance, error categories. |
| **Workflow impact** | Cycle time, rework, queue age, defect containment time, planner effort, response speed. |
| **Safety / risk** | Policy violations, prohibited actions, hallucination/false recommendation severity, unauthorized access. |
| **Economic value** | Measured benefit compared with case assumptions and implementation/operating cost. |
| **Operational readiness** | Support, monitoring, ownership, data refresh, incident response, user training. |

