# 19. Common failure modes and recovery actions

| Failure mode | Warning sign | Recovery action |
|---|---|---|
| **Innovation theater** | Success is counted as demos, hackathons, or number of ideas. | Shift metrics to qualified opportunities, pilots, adoption, and realized value. |
| **Technology-first ideation** | “Where can we use agents?” is the opening question. | Start with outcome, workflow, decision, baseline, and non-AI options. |
| **Pilot purgatory** | A proof of concept “went well” but has no scale decision. | Define scale/stop gates, owner, funding path, and production requirements before pilot start. |
| **No business owner** | Many people are interested, but nobody owns the KPI. | Do not fund until sponsor/process owner accountability is explicit. |
| **Vague ROI** | “It will save a lot of time.” | Demand a baseline, volume, adoption estimate, conversion mechanism, and finance partner. |
| **Late governance** | Security, quality, OT, or legal appear at the end. | Risk-tier in discovery and involve the right partners before solution selection. |
| **Overbuilding the platform** | A giant AI platform is proposed before a validated demand pattern exists. | Build modular foundations only where repeated use-case evidence justifies them. |
| **Underbuilding controls** | A prototype is pushed into operational use with no monitoring/evaluation/rollback. | Use explicit autonomy levels, evaluation gates, logging, support, and safe fallback. |
| **Ignoring frontline workflow** | Users say the solution is useful but do not use it. | Observe work, co-design, change SOPs/training, and measure adoption. |
| **Assuming one-site success scales** | A solution breaks at another plant/product line. | Treat transferability as a hypothesis; plan replication waves and local variation. |
| **Treating data readiness as a binary** | “We have data” but no context, quality, ownership, or access. | Map source, semantics, time alignment, quality, ownership, and permissions. |
| **Executive overpromising** | Large value claims precede evidence. | Communicate hypotheses and ranges; maintain a decision log and measured outcomes. |

